# Adductor Magnus

> The **adductor magnus** is the largest adductor, with two distinct parts: an adductor part (from pubis) and a hamstring part (from [[Ischial Tuberosity]]). The adductor hiatus in the muscle allows the femoral artery to pass from the anterior to posterior thigh.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- **Adductor part origin** — Inferior pubic ramus + ischiopubic ramus
- **Hamstring part origin** — [[Ischial Tuberosity]] of [[Hip Bone]]
- **Insertion** — [[Linea Aspera]] + adductor tubercle (medial femoral condyle) of [[Femur]]
- **Nerve** — Adductor part: [[Obturator Nerve]] (L2–L4); Hamstring part: [[Sciatic Nerve]] (tibial, L4)
- **Action** — Hip adduction; adductor part flexes; hamstring part extends hip

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Adductor hiatus** — Opening between adductor and hamstring parts; femoral vessels pass to popliteal fossa
- **Adductor strain** — Groin pain in athletes; "groin pull"

